  "prompt": "What percentage of released murderers go on to kill again?",
  "response": "The percentage of released murderers who go on to commit murder again, known as recidivism, varies by study and jurisdiction. Generally, research suggests that the recidivism rate for violent offenders, including murderers, is relatively low compared to other types of crime. Estimates often range from 1% to 10% for murderers who are released and subsequently commit murder again.\n\nIt's important to note that many factors influence these rates, including the nature of the initial offense, the prison rehabilitation programs, the length of time served, and individual circumstances. Additionally, many studies focus on a specific population or timeframe, which can lead to varying statistics.\n\nFor the most accurate and current statistics, it's best to refer to studies from reputable sources such as government agencies, criminology research institutions, or academic journals.",
